Ah, a Wikipedia article. How quaint. You want me to expand on a stadium. Fine. But don't expect me to wax poetic about grandstands and foul poles. I'll give you the facts, laced with a healthy dose of *reality*. And if you find yourself… affected… by my prose, that’s on you.

***

## Harbor Park

Harbor Park, a structure primarily dedicated to the glorious, yet often agonizing, pursuit of baseball, sits perched on the edge of the [Elizabeth River](/Elizabeth_River_(Virginia)) in the heart of [Norfolk, Virginia](/Norfolk,_Virginia). Once lauded by the esteemed publication [Baseball America](/Baseball_America) as the pinnacle of minor league baseball stadiums, it now serves as the hallowed ground for the [Norfolk Tides](/Norfolk_Tides), a team that competes in [Minor League Baseball](/Minor_League_Baseball) within the venerable [International League](/International_League). This establishment, Harbor Park, officially swung open its gates on April 14, 1993, capable of accommodating a throng of 12,067 souls, though that number has seen some slight adjustments over the years. The Tides, for those who haven't been paying attention, are the [Triple-A](/Triple-A_(baseball)) affiliate of the [Baltimore Orioles](/Baltimore_Orioles).

### Features

The seating arrangement at Harbor Park is a carefully orchestrated affair: 9,000 seats are nestled on the lower deck, while an additional 2,800 grace the upper deck. For those who prefer their baseball experience with a side of al fresco dining, there's a picnic area with a capacity for 300, strategically placed in the outfield. If your tastes lean towards the more… *exclusive*, the stadium boasts 24 luxury skyboxes, each capable of holding 400 guests, and a full-service restaurant that seats 225, offering a panoramic vista of the field from the first base side. It’s worth noting that the stadium has seen its share of packed houses; a record attendance of 14,263 was etched into the books on August 31, 1996, a testament to the collective desire for… *something*.

The playing surface itself is a meticulously maintained expanse of natural grass, equipped with a sophisticated irrigation and drainage system designed to withstand the whims of nature. The dimensions of the outfield are as follows: 333 feet to the left field foul pole, a commanding 400 feet to straightaway center field, and a more intimate 318 feet down the right field line.

In a bid to keep pace with the ever-evolving demands of spectator entertainment, the stadium underwent a significant upgrade prior to the 2022 season, with the installation of a pair of video boards. Their combined size, I'm told, is the largest in the minor leagues. The main video board, replacing the previous [scoreboard](/Scoreboard) in right field, measures an impressive 32 by 114 feet (9.75 by 34.75 [meters](/Metre)), making it second only to the behemoth at [Las Vegas Ballpark](/Las_Vegas_Ballpark). A secondary, albeit still substantial, video board is situated in left field, measuring 24 by 60 feet (7.32 by 18.29 meters). Both were brought to life by the technological prowess of [Daktronics](/Daktronics).

During the 1990s, Harbor Park also played host to the gridiron battles of Norfolk's high school football teams, namely [Maury](/Matthew_Fontaine_Maury_High_School), [Granby](/Granby_High_School), and [Booker T. Washington](/Booker_T._Washington_High_School_(Norfolk,_Virginia)). However, the landscape shifted. In 1996, BTW established its own stadium, and by 2005, Maury and Granby had migrated to the newly constructed Powhatan Field. While Harbor Park once served as a venue for high school football postseason contests, that tradition ceased in 2012. Apparently, even football has its limits.

### Transportation

For those who prefer not to rely on their own questionable navigation skills, [The Tide](/Tide_Light_Rail), Norfolk's light rail system, conveniently offers a station along Park Avenue, practically at the stadium's doorstep. Amtrak, the purveyor of punctual (or not so punctual) rail travel, also has its [Norfolk station](/Norfolk_station_(Amtrak)) adjacent to Harbor Park. Proximity is, after all, a valuable commodity.

### Notable events

Harbor Park has been the backdrop for a variety of events, some more significant than others. In 1998, it played host to the [Triple-A All-Star Game](/Triple-A_All-Star_Game), where the International League All-Stars decisively defeated their [Pacific Coast League](/Pacific_Coast_League) counterparts by a score of 8–4. A rather anticlimactic outcome, if you ask me.

During [Major League Baseball](/Major_League_Baseball)'s rather public search for a new home for the [Montreal Expos](/Montreal_Expos), Norfolk put forth a proposal to expand Harbor Park to accommodate a major league team, albeit temporarily. The bid, however, was ultimately rejected, and the Expos found their new home in Washington, D.C., becoming the [Washington Nationals](/Washington_Nationals). A missed opportunity, perhaps, or a bullet dodged, depending on your perspective.

On March 30, 2007, the [Washington Nationals](/Washington_Nationals) and the [Baltimore Orioles](/Baltimore_Orioles) engaged in an exhibition game at Harbor Park. The event, a sell-out two weeks in advance, drew a crowd of 12,408 spectators. The two teams, along with the Tides, have engaged in further exhibition matches in subsequent years, including in 2009, 2012, 2014, and 2018. It seems the allure of seeing professional players in a minor league setting is a persistent one.

In a slightly less athletic vein, on October 28, 2008, Harbor Park was the venue for a rally hosted by [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama). A gathering of supporters, no doubt energized by the promise of change, or perhaps just the free air.

A more recent addition to the stadium's amenities came in December 2008, when the city of Norfolk approved a plan by the Tides to construct a party deck in right field, situated behind the home team's bullpen. Completed in March 2009, just before an Orioles–Nationals exhibition game, this deck can accommodate 400 people. While it didn't technically increase the stadium's overall capacity, it certainly added a new dimension, especially during sold-out games where it could absorb some overflow. This construction also necessitated a slight adjustment to the right field fence, moving it inward by 20 feet to its current distance of 318 feet.

The concert band piece *Harbor Park Holiday*, composed in 1996 by Norfolk native James L. Hosay, was, as the title suggests, inspired by this very stadium. A rather niche homage, but one that speaks to the place's significance in local culture.

And for a truly bizarre footnote, on August 30, 2019, Harbor Park hosted the RIP Paul Walker [fantasy football](/Fantasy_football_(American)) draft party. Actor [Leslie David Baker](/Leslie_David_Baker), known for his role in the hit television show [The Office](/The_Office_(American_TV_series)), was reportedly in attendance. One can only imagine the conversations that transpired.

